This is a known breaking change. Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE`, and .NET 10 MAUI no longer supports it. Here's how to fix it:

## Option 1 — Quick fix: Switch to `AdjustPan`

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
[Activity(WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustPan)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

This scrolls the whole window up so the focused input stays visible. Works for simple layouts but can hide your header/toolbar.

## Option 2 — Recommended: Handle keyboard insets (edge-to-edge)

Listen for IME insets and adjust your layout's bottom padding:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
using AndroidX.Core.View;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
            Window!.DecorView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
    }

    class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(
            Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use the larger of IME or nav bar bottom inset
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

Then set soft input mode to `AdjustNothing` so the system doesn't fight your layout:

```csharp
[Activity(WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustNothing)]
```

This gives you the old `Resize`-like behavior — your content area shrinks and the input bar slides up above the keyboard, while keeping your toolbar visible.

**TL;DR:** `AdjustPan` is the one-liner fix. For full control (like the old `Resize` behavior), handle `WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()` yourself.
